Beijing's natural ecology continues to improve, attracting more than 500 species of wild animals to "settle" in the city - Chinanews.com
2020-07-26 05:03:17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The capital's natural ecology continues to improve, attracting wildlife to "settle" in the city
There are more than 500 species of wild animals in Beijing
A reporter from Beijing Youth Daily learned from the Municipal Landscaping Bureau that in recent years, with the continuous improvement of the capital's natural ecological environment, the types and numbers of wild animals have also continued to increase.
At present, the number of terrestrial vertebrate wild animals inhabiting Beijing has increased to more than 500, including national first-class protected animals such as brown horse pheasant and black stork, as well as national second-class protected animals such as impala, whooper swan, gray crane and mandarin duck.
Whether it is an urban forest planted in the Second Ring Road or a small wetland embedded between buildings, it not only brings the wild interest of nature to the citizens of the capital, but also attracts wild animals to "settle" in the city.
In the middle of summer, the Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in the Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is full of life.
A raccoon dog is playing leisurely by a mountain stream, while two badgers are playing with each other.
Looking back, a wild boar couldn't resist the "stinging" on its body and was rubbing against the bark of the tree. Hu Qiaoli, director of the management office of Songshan National Nature Reserve, said that by the end of 2019, in this green sea with a total area of more than 6,200 hectares, there were 178 species of wild animals, including the golden eagle, a national first-class protected animal, and spoon chicken, and impala, which are national second-class protected animals, and nearly one-third of the city's wild animal species can be seen here.
"In Matsuyama, wild animals are the real 'owners', and our staff can only be regarded as people's 'bodyguards' at best. ”
Hu Qiaoli said that in order to learn about the wildlife in the reserve, more than 30 professional rangers patrol along 16 carefully formulated conservation routes every day, and there is a "big circle" every month, spending a whole day to visit almost the entire reserve.
"During the inspection, it is not only necessary to check and record the biodiversity, but also to check the installation of artificial bird nests, rescue injured wild animals, install infrared cameras in the field, and so on. ”
More than 200 infrared cameras have been installed in Songshan National Nature Reserve to record the living conditions of wild animals in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli introduced that with the continuous enrichment of biodiversity in the reserve in recent years, more and more wild animals have appeared in the camera, leopard cats, raccoon dogs and badgers have become "resident guests", and the "appearance rate" of impala, a national second-class protected animal, is also getting higher and higher.
Zhang Zhiming, director of the Wildlife and Wetland Conservation Division of the Beijing Municipal Bureau of Landscaping and Landscaping, said that the number of terrestrial vertebrate wild animals in Beijing has increased from 461 in 1994 to more than 500 now, and the variety and number of wild animals in Beijing have continued to increase in recent years.
Wildlife is becoming more and more common in cities, which is closely related to the continuous upgrading of urban greening in the capital in recent years.
In particular, a new round of afforestation and greening construction of one million mu started in 2018 proposes to reshape the urban ecological environment, improve the ecological function of woodland and green space, and highlight the concept of "near nature".
In terms of planning, it strives to achieve interconnection and interaction with the surrounding green space, so that wild animals can "visit relatives and friends", and the trees planted are also the nectar and food source plants that animals love.
Black soil "grows" agricultural modernization-Xinhuanet
Harbin, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Black soil "grows" agricultural modernization
In the middle of summer, two spraying planes swept past the 10,000 mu high-yield demonstration field of the second operation station of the fifth management area of the friendship farm, forming two white lines, and the big words "the first in the world" planted with black rice seedlings in the green field are particularly eye-catching.
Kong Lingqiang, head of the station, said that this kind of aircraft can spray pesticides on more than 6,000 acres of cultivated land in a day, and the efficiency is about eight times that of drones and hundreds of times that of manual labor.
This farm is located in Youyi County, Heilongjiang Province, China's largest grain-producing province, from the past "swish" rice cutting sound to the current "rumbling" motor sound, Chinese traditional farming and farms in this black soil belt to achieve transformation.
In addition to aircraft, satellites are also used in modern agricultural production at Friendship Farms.
Kong Lingqiang introduced that on the one hand, they use satellite remote sensing technology to achieve precise fertilization, reduce agricultural inputs, reduce pollution, on the other hand, satellite navigation technology can improve the level of standardized operation of agricultural machinery in the field.
In this year's rice production process, the farm expanded the operating area of satellite navigation unmanned rice transplanting technology from 3,000 mu last year to 30,000 mu.
This technology makes the seedlings planted more evenly, which can maximize the use of sunlight and cultivated land resources, and can also save 16 yuan per mu of labor costs.
The farm has tried new technologies such as informatization and intelligence in agricultural production, and has formed the largest agricultural machinery group in China from the ground to the sky.
According to statistics, the total number of farm machinery is 49,000 units (pieces), and the comprehensive mechanization rate in the field is 99.8%.
100% of agricultural machinery operations have achieved GPS satellite navigation, 100% precision sowing in dry fields, and 100% of high-horsepower locomotive operations in dry fields.
"Green agriculture, smart agriculture and digital agriculture are the directions for agricultural modernization. ”
Liu Hualian, director of Friendship Farm, said.
The key to agricultural modernization lies in scientific and technological progress.
In recent years, Heilongjiang Agricultural Reclamation, represented by farms, has played a demonstration and leading role as the "aircraft carrier" of modern agriculture, and has initially established a modern agricultural industrial system dominated by large-scale planting, standardized production and industrialized operation.
On the outskirts of Youyi County, there is an Agricultural Machinery Expo Park covering an area of 350,000 square meters.
More than 140 sets (pieces) of agricultural machinery and tools that have been introduced and used by Heilongjiang Agricultural Reclamation over the years are exhibited here.
These agricultural machinery and farms have witnessed the development of China's agricultural modernization.
Giving up a small home for everyone - Anhui Hefei Jiangkou River Lianwei mass transfer direct hit-Xinhuanet
Hefei, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The transfer of the masses in Jiangkouhe, Hefei, Anhui Province, is a direct blow to the masses
Xinhua News Agency reporters Chen Shangying, Wang Liwu, and Liu Xiacun
At around 4 p.m. on July 25, Fu Kunbao wore mud-covered rubber shoes, from the front room to the back room, and his wife Zhou Yan were busy packing up their things back and forth.
"After receiving a call from the village cadres to transfer the village, I was still picking grass in the field. ”
Fu Kunbao said that he has transferred more than 60 acres of land, planted rice, and is growing well now. ”
Fu Kunbao pointed to the pesticide sprayer placed in the corner, "No one wants their home to be flooded, so let's give up a small family for everyone." ”
In order to cope with the continuous high water pressure and possible heavy rainfall in Chaohu Lake, Hefei City, Anhui Province, is preparing to open the Jiangkou River Lianwei flood storage on the 26th, where Fu Kunbao's house is located.
Jiangkou River Lianwei is located in Feixi County, close to Chaohu Lake Embankment.
There are thousands of villagers involved in Yandian Township and Sanhe Township who need to be relocated.
As of 16 o'clock on the 25th, the water level of Chaohu Lake, the fifth largest freshwater lake in China, remained at a high level of 13.2 meters, exceeding the guaranteed water level by 0.7 meters.
Fu Kunbao's kitchen was clean, with a pot of pumpkin head vegetables on the table, eggs and some braised vegetables in the refrigerator.
"I didn't expect to move, the water of the Jiangkou River is currently good. ”
Zhou Yan said that the home is a bungalow, and some large objects have not been thought about where to put them for the time being.
"Pack up your valuables first, and you can temporarily put large items such as refrigerators and televisions at the homes of neighbors or relatives on high ground. ”
Wang Liwen, a village cadre, gave Fu Kunbao an idea.
Wang Liwen was responsible for the relocation and resettlement of 13 villagers, notifying each household and confirming the resettlement plan for each person.
The closest resettlement point to Fu Kunbao's house is Su Primary School in Yandian Township, about 2 kilometers away.
In addition to the large items, Fu Kunbao and his family also had a headache of more than 1,000 catties of food and some newly bought furniture at home.
"The food was going to be dragged to the relative's house, and the furniture couldn't be moved. ”
As soon as the couple discussed, they put a stool under the newly bought bed and raised the bed by about half a meter.
At 6 p.m., Fu Kunbao began to use a tricycle to transport things to relatives' houses, and Zhou Yan continued to clean up at home.
At around 11 o'clock in the evening, the couple looked back and forth at home, pulled the electric switch, and prepared to go to the resettlement site.
"I hope the water recedes soon. ”
Fu Kunbao said.
At half past nine o'clock in the morning of July 26, the reporter saw at the scene of Jiangkou River Lianwei that the local government had made various preparations before flood distribution.
