The engine may stall, and the FAA urgently ordered 2,000 Boeing airliners-Xinhuanet
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring emergency inspections of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic passenger aircraft registered in the United States, because the air check valve of the above-mentioned passenger aircraft may be corroded and the engine may stop in the air.
The FAA stated that, to date, it had received four reports of 737NG and 737Classic aircraft engine stops in the air, and had therefore requested urgent inspections of aircraft that had been parked for seven days or more and for aircraft that had flown less than 11 times to date since they were re-commissioned.
The FAA has warned that if the 5th stage check valves of all two engines of the airliner are corroded, they could get stuck in the open position, causing the airliner to lose power completely and unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that if a corroded check valve is found, the airline operator must replace this critical component before the aircraft can be put into service again.
Boeing responded later in the day that the coronavirus outbreak had reduced travel demand, and many passenger planes were mothballed or less used, and "check valves are more likely to corrode".
At the same time, Boeing said that it has advised airline operators to inspect the airliners covered by the directive, and if problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in overhauling and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that the planes of major U.S. airlines typically fly multiple times a day, but a large number of passenger planes were grounded after the coronavirus outbreak, and some have reopened operations as passenger travel demand has slowly increased recently.
The FAA did not release details of the four reports on air parking.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents late on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that one of its airliners was en route from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas, on July 15 when an engine suddenly stalled and the plane made an emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the plane's engines and had inspected the engines of six planes in accordance with FAA directives.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines respectively said on the 24th that their passenger planes did not have an engine stall associated with an air check valve.
Four American Airlines planes will be inspected, and 28 United Airlines planes will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect its 20 planes, but did not say if there had been engine stalls.
Several media outlets reported that the FAA's emergency airworthiness directive was another blow to Boeing.
One Boeing 737 MAX each of Indonesia's Lion Air and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019, killing a total of 346 people.
The series of aircraft was subsequently grounded worldwide, production was discontinued in January this year, and production resumed in May.
FAA Administrator Steve Dixon admitted in June that the FAA had "erroneously" in its oversight of Boeing over the 737 MAX.
