For the first time, the United States launched a countervailing investigation against China on the grounds that the RMB exchange rate was undervalued
In response to the recent announcement of the U.S. Department of Commerce, it decided to launch an anti-dumping and countervailing investigation on cable ties (cable ties) products originating in China, and launched an investigation on the "undervaluation of the RMB exchange rate" project.
China's Ministry of Commerce pointed out that this is the first time that the United States has opened a case to investigate the so-called "undervaluation of the RMB exchange rate" in a countervailing case, and China firmly opposes this.
China's Ministry of Commerce issued a special press release on the evening of the 23rd, stating that China implements a managed floating exchange rate system based on market supply and demand, adjusted with reference to a basket of currencies, and the market plays a decisive role in the formation of the exchange rate.
The press release stressed that overall, the RMB exchange rate is at a reasonable and balanced level and is not undervalued.
Since 2005, the renminbi has appreciated by more than 17% against the US dollar.
According to the data released by the Bank for International Settlements, from the beginning of 2005 to May 2020, the nominal effective exchange rate of the renminbi appreciated by 38%, and the real effective exchange rate appreciated by 49%, making it the strongest currency among the G20 economies and one of the largest currencies in the world.
The Commerce Department noted that the exchange rate issue exceeded the competence of members to conduct countervailing investigations under World Trade Organization rules.
In February this year, the United States amended its laws and regulations to conduct a countervailing investigation on the exchange rates of other countries, which is suspected of violating WTO rules and has been opposed by many quarters.
The press release said that even under U.S. regulations, the applicant's complaint contained a large number of errors and did not meet the necessary countervailing elements such as financial assistance, benefit awarding and specificity.
China urges the US to abide by existing international rules and stop conducting countervailing investigations on the so-called "undervaluation of the renminbi exchange rate".
Affected by the further escalation of tensions between China and the United States, the offshore and onshore RMB exchange rates against the US dollar depreciated sharply on the 22nd, both falling below the 7.0 yuan mark of 1 US dollar against the yuan.
It will be interesting to see whether the U.S. Department of Commerce's move is intended to force the renminbi to rise.
The spot exchange rate of RMB against the US dollar rose above the 7.0 mark on the 23rd and closed at 6.9961.
The central parity of the RMB exchange rate against the US dollar, which is regulated by the government, was lowered by 17 basis points to 6.9938 on the 24th.
