The Tibetan antelope of Hoh Xili enters the migration season-Xinhuanet
Xining, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The reporter learned from the Wudaoliang Protection Station of the Hoh Xil Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration that monitoring shows that the Tibetan antelopes that had previously migrated to the Zhuo Nai Lake area in the hinterland of Hoh Xil to give birth are successively finishing their littering and beginning to return to their original habitat with their young.
Surveillance footage near the Wudaoliang Protection Station shows that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelopes led three Tibetan antelope cubs through the 3,002 kilometers of the Qinghai-Tibet Highway and the Wudaoliang North Bridge of the Qinghai-Tibet Railway, and the Tibetan antelope has begun to move back.
According to expert analysis, in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope pups in the relocated sheep herd has accounted for one-quarter to one-fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelope herds.
Lian Xinming, an associate researcher at the Northwest Institute of Plateau Biology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: "In the early days of migration, the Tibetan antelope faces a high risk of predation, so the number of pups in the flock will be relatively small, and there may even be no pups. ”
According to the statistics of the Hoh Xil Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the number of Tibetan antelopes returning has been increasing year by year, with 4,860 Tibetan antelopes returning in 2019, an increase of 338 over 2018.
Lian Xinming said: "It is expected that the return of Tibetan antelopes will end in early September this year, and the number of Tibetan antelopes returning is still expected to continue to increase." ”
The Tibetan antelope is a national first-class protected animal.
At the end of May every year, Tibetan antelopes from the source of the three rivers in Qinghai, the Qiangtang in Tibet, and the Altun Mountains in Xinjiang go to Zhuo Nai Lake in the hinterland of Hoh Xil to give lambs.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert in Tibetan antelope conservation in China and a researcher at the Shaanxi Provincial Institute of Zoology (Northwest Institute of Endangered Animals), said: "The migration of Tibetan antelopes is a process in which female Tibetan antelopes return to their habitats with their young after giving birth. Initially, large groups of returnees leave their farrowing sites, but then Tibetan antelopes will return to their respective habitats along different paths depending on the geographical population. ”
In order to ensure the safe return of the Tibetan antelope herd, the reporter learned that the Hoh Xil Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration has arranged staff to continue to carry out video monitoring and patrol in the main relocation area.
If a herd of Tibetan antelopes is found trying to cross the road, the patrol team will immediately carry out temporary traffic control to allow the sheep to pass safely through the wildlife passage and ensure that they are least disturbed by humans on the way back.
So, how to relieve the heat in daily life?
Experts recommend that when going out in the summer, try to avoid hot periods, and it is best not to walk or work in the scorching sun around noon, because the sun is most intense during this time period, and the possibility of heat stroke is higher.
If you must go out during this time, you must do a good job of protection, such as wearing a parasol, wearing a sunhat, wearing sunglasses, and it is best to apply sunscreen if possible to prevent sunburn.
Try to choose light-colored, breathable cotton, linen and silk textures, and wear less chemical fiber clothing, so as not to dissipate heat in time when sweating a lot, causing heat stroke.
In hot and sultry weather, you should prepare enough water to drink, drink it in time, don't wait until you are thirsty to drink water, because once you feel thirsty, your body is already short of water, drink water at 150 ml to 200 ml each time, drink warm water, do not drink ice water.
Depending on the temperature, the average person drinks 1.5 to 2 liters of water per day, and the high-temperature workers drink 3 to 5 liters of water per day.
When you sweat a lot, you can properly supplement some salt water to make up for the salt lost by the human body due to sweating.
In addition, the human body is prone to potassium deficiency in summer, making people feel tired and tired, potassium-containing tea is an excellent drink to cool off.
In summer, eat more fruits and vegetables with high water content, such as lettuce, cucumbers, tomatoes, etc., fresh fruits, such as peaches, apricots, watermelons, melons, etc., with a water content of 80% to 90%, can be used to replenish water, and dairy products can not only replenish water, but also meet the body's nutritional needs.
In addition, people who work in a high-temperature environment should appropriately supplement drinks containing potassium, magnesium and other elements.
In summer, the days are long and the nights are short, the temperature is high, the body's metabolism is vigorous, the consumption is also large, and it is easy to feel fatigue.
Adequate sleep can relax the brain and body systems, which is not only conducive to work and study, but also a measure to prevent heat stroke.
Experts say that the best time to go to bed is between 10 p.m. and 11 p.m., and the best time to wake up is between 5:30 a.m. and 6:30 a.m.
Be careful not to lie down under the air vent of the air conditioner and the electric fan when sleeping, so as not to suffer from air conditioning sickness and heat cold.
Experts suggest that people who are outdoors or working in high temperatures can carry ten drops of water, Rendan, Huoxiang Zhengqi Water or Huoxiang Zhengqi Pills and other heatstroke prevention medicines, or place them in the nearest workplace and use them at any time to prevent heat stroke.
