SYDNEY, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Researchers at Monash University in Australia are developing a new drug that could help prevent heart disease and stroke, and hope it could be used to treat blockages in blood vessels caused by the coronavirus.
Researchers have found that before a heart attack or stroke, an enzyme in platelets accelerates platelet clotting.
As a result, they developed a drug that can temporarily inhibit platelet clotting, thereby preventing blood vessel clogging and preventing heart disease and stroke.
Researchers say the drug only inhibits the clotting effect of platelets at the appearance of signs of heart disease or stroke.
Since studies have shown that similar blockages of blood vessels are one of the leading causes of death in patients with severe COVID, the researchers hope that the drug can be used in the treatment of such severe patients in the future.
At present, the drug has achieved good results in animal model experiments, and researchers are preparing for the next stage of human clinical trials.
The research results have been published in the American journal Science Translational Medicine.
