The so-called false negative means that the person tested is indeed infected, but the nucleic acid test result is negative.
In addition, for people who have had close contact with confirmed or suspected cases, two nucleic acid tests are usually required to rule them out.
For people who have been to medium- and high-risk areas of the epidemic, if they have fever and respiratory symptoms, there is a possibility of false negatives if they have a negative nucleic acid test, so two nucleic acid tests are also needed to rule it out.
