APEC Trade Ministers' Meeting Says It Will Accelerate Regional Economic Recovery-Xinhuanet
KUALA LUMPUR, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) trade ministers held a virtual meeting on July 25, at which they pledged to work to reduce the impact of the new crown epidemic on the region's economy and accelerate the realization of a resilient, sustainable and inclusive regional economic recovery.
The meeting was chaired by Malaysia, the host of this year's APEC Leaders' Informal Meeting.
The joint statement issued after the meeting said that APEC trade ministers recognize the importance of a free, open, fair, non-discriminatory, transparent and predictable trade and investment environment to promote economic recovery at this challenging time.
The parties pledged to ensure that emergency measures taken in response to the pandemic are targeted, appropriate, transparent and temporary, do not create unnecessary trade barriers and disrupt global supply chains, while complying with World Trade Organization rules.
In a statement, APEC trade ministers pledged to strengthen cooperation to facilitate the flow of essential goods and services, promote connectivity by strengthening supply chain resilience, and minimize disruptions to the flow of medical supplies, food and agricultural products in response to the pandemic.
APEC trade ministers agreed on the need to discuss how to reduce non-tariff barriers that restrict trade in essential goods, and reaffirmed their commitment to facilitating the necessary cross-border movement of people without compromising measures taken to stop the spread of the virus.
The conference also issued a declaration on the promotion of the flow of essential commodities.
The declaration said that economies will ensure that the trade measures they take in response to the epidemic are in line with WTO regulations, and commit to take actions in reducing non-tariff trade barriers and trade facilitation to facilitate the flow of goods necessary during the epidemic.
Malaysia's Minister of International Trade and Industry, Azmin Ali, who chaired the meeting, said that despite the impact of the pandemic, Malaysia is still committed to the success of this year's APEC meeting, and the work of formulating a vision for cooperation beyond APEC2020 is progressing in an orderly manner.
Malaysia agreed to hold APEC-related meetings virtually, but did not rule out the possibility of arranging physical meetings at the end of the year during the informal meeting of APEC leaders.
