Is it reasonable for a 3-year-old child to sue the school after being compensated for being smashed in the college playground?
2020-07-26 05:01:11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The playground was smashed, and the children sued the school after receiving compensation
□ Zhao Yifan, correspondent of this newspaper
3-year-old Xiaowen was playing in a college playground when he was accidentally hit in the head by Chen of the softball team while pitching.
After Chen compensated, Xiaowen's father, Mr. Wen, as Xiaowen's legal representative, sued the school to the court, demanding that the school where the playground occurred apologize and pay a total of 20,000 yuan for medical expenses and mental damages.
Recently, after hearing the case, the Beijing Haidian District People's Court held that the school had set up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, and had fulfilled its appropriate safety and security obligations, and Chen had made compensation, so the judgment rejected the plaintiff's claim.
Mr. Wen complained that during the summer vacation of 2019, he took Xiaowen to play in the school playground, which was where the softball team was training.
In order to avoid the risks brought by this, Xiaowen, Mr. Wen and many other children and their parents moved around in the safe area designated by the softball team.
However, Chen, a member of the softball team, later dropped off while pitching, causing the softball to fly over the net into the safety zone and hit the back of the ball.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment, where he was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Man believes that the facilities of the school stadium do not comply with the relevant safety regulations and the team and related facilities are not effectively managed.
The school's negligence led to the above-mentioned incident, which caused Xiaowen to suffer great physical and mental suffering, and also brought great suffering to his family, for which the school should bear legal responsibility.
In this regard, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net in the playground, and posted management regulations and training notices, informing them that they must keep a safe distance from the training site and remind them to pay attention to their own safety, and that the plaintiff could not prove that the school had "failed to fulfill its safety and security obligations", so it did not agree to compensation.
After hearing the case, the court held that the venue where the incident occurred was a venue open to the public free of charge by the university involved in the case, and although the university had a safety guarantee obligation for the management of the playground, such a safety guarantee obligation only required to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school had set up a protective net in the playground, and had fulfilled its appropriate safety and security obligations, and Chen also compensated Xiaowen for medical expenses, transportation expenses and other losses of more than 2,000 yuan in accordance with the compensation agreement reached before, and the two parties agreed to settle the dispute at one time.
Afterwards, Xiaowen's parents again claimed compensation from the school, but there was no basis in law, and the court rejected all of the plaintiff's claims.
After the verdict was pronounced, neither party appealed, and the verdict is now in force.
According to Article 37 of the Tort Liability Law of the People's Republic of China, the school, as the manager of a public place, has the obligation to ensure safety, and if the act of a third party causes damage to others, the third party shall bear the tort liability, and the manager of the public place who fails to fulfill the obligation of safety and security shall bear the corresponding supplementary liability.
According to the judge, since as the manager of a public place, he is most likely to understand the actual situation of the entire place, foresee the dangers and damages that may occur, and is therefore most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of losses or mitigate the extent of damages, and the cost of avoiding and mitigating the occurrence of damages is the lowest, so the law stipulates that he bears the corresponding obligation to protect his engagement in social activities.
In this case, the school's obligation to ensure the safety of unspecified people entering the playground that is open to the public free of charge should be commensurate with the social activities they are engaged in, specifically, it should mainly take basic safety measures and have the obligation to inform about hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is also not appropriate to impose excessively high security obligations on managers of public places.
If the school has already taken measures to set up a protective net and fulfilled its obligation to inform, it can be determined that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, for third-party infringement, even if the manager of a public place such as a school fails to fulfill its safety and security obligations, the liability borne by the manager is a supplement to damages, and according to the newly promulgated Civil Code, the manager can recover from the third party after assuming the supplementary liability.
Therefore, in such an accident, the victim should not expand the scope of compensation after receiving compensation from the direct infringer.
