Israel has strengthened its prevention and control of repeated epidemics
In the early days of the pandemic, Israel's containment measures were effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of prevention and control measures, the number of confirmed cases of new crown pneumonia in Israel has increased significantly recently, and the Israeli government has taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic many times.
On February 28, the first case of new coronavirus pneumonia was confirmed in Israel, and the military and police jointly maintained prevention and control measures, such as closing all ports of entry and exit, suspending non-essential industries, changing schools to online classes, restricting public transportation and non-essential social activities, locking down cities with severe epidemics, and joint maintenance of prevention and control measures by the military and police.
This series of measures quickly paid off with positive results, and by mid-May, the number of new confirmed cases of new coronavirus pneumonia in Israel had dropped to single digits in a single day.
As the epidemic is under control and Israel's prevention and control measures are fully lifted, the number of new confirmed cases of new coronavirus pneumonia has gradually rebounded since June.
Especially since July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, the number of new daily cases in Israel has exceeded 1,500 for eight days, and as of press time on July 25, the number of new cases on that day reached 916.
As of July 25, there were 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths in Israel.
In the face of the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed gyms, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs and other places of public entertainment, while introducing a policy of restricting public transportation, stipulating that each bus could not have more than 20 passengers.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictions, including the implementation of a "lockdown" on weekends, stipulating that a "lockdown" will be implemented from 5 p.m. every Friday to 5 p.m. every Sunday.
During this period, people can go out, but establishments such as shops, shopping malls, hairdressers, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while essential services such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people are prohibited on all dates and time slots, gyms, studios and other establishments will be closed, restaurants and cafes will be closed for dine-in, and only takeaway services will be allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people have not paid enough attention to the severity of the epidemic and have not been able to form a joint force with the government in the fight against the epidemic.
After the resurgence of the epidemic in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest and march because the government's prevention and control measures affected their economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people demonstrated in Tel Aviv, arguing that anti-epidemic policies were affecting the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands of protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu's official residence in Jerusalem to protest against Prime Minister Netanyahu's promulgation of prevention and control measures such as banning dine-in in restaurants and cafes without giving corresponding compensation.
In addition, many people do not follow the rules of wearing masks and maintaining a two-meter safe social distance when they are outdoors, and many people only wear masks on their chins or wrists to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks.
According to a recent visit to the kindergarten, the teachers and students in the kindergarten did not wear masks as required by the government, nor did they maintain a safe social distance of two meters from each other, laying a hidden danger for a large number of teachers and students to be infected with the virus.
Professor Eli Waxman, a member of the Expert Advisory Group on the Fight against the Epidemic at the National Security Council of Israel, believes that Israel is heading towards a "dangerous situation", noting that the current epidemic prevention and control measures in Israel are not enough, and all leisure and entertainment venues and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks an overall plan to fight the epidemic, and that the parliament and government departments should put aside their own interests as soon as possible, reach an agreement on the fight against the epidemic, and formulate clear steps that include relevant restrictions in different sectors.
