The Lancet published an article praising China's anti-epidemic efforts and encouraging other countries to learn from their experiences-Chinanews.com
The Lancet magazine published an article on the 25th saying that China, as a country with a population of 1.4 billion and a size similar to that of Europe or the United States, has effectively controlled the new crown epidemic at this stage, and there has been no large-scale transmission, which has largely controlled the domestic epidemic.
In the past decade or so, China has invested heavily in domestic research and public health, which has made China's preparedness for the new crown much better than it was for severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) back then, the article said.
The authors say that when the SARS outbreak occurred in 2002, China was initially ill-prepared, especially because the pathogen could not be identified.
When the novel coronavirus was discovered in December 2019, Chinese scientists were quickly able to identify the virus species and shared the genome sequencing data with the international community on January 11, 2020.
By the end of January, doctors from Chinese mainland and Hong Kong had elucidated the clinical features of the virus, warning the world of the threat of the coronavirus through a research paper published in The Lancet.
China has also been at the forefront of vaccine research, which has been carried out very quickly and rigorously through close domestic cooperation amid the declaration of a state of emergency, with the results of progress in early trials of a Chinese-developed COVID vaccine published in The Lancet in May and July, respectively.
China's experience shows that it is important to invest in national health and research systems to effectively improve laboratory capacity.
This is the basis for a rapid and effective national response to health emergencies and global health security.
Other countries, especially low- and middle-income countries, have a lot to learn from.
In addition, China's experience has proven that the pandemic can be effectively brought under control by a strong high-level and decisive scientific evidence, based on strong research.
The article stresses that governments and their leaders must respect science, understand its value, and act on it in the best interests of society.
In the early days of the outbreak, China's National Health Commission sent three teams of infectious disease experts to Wuhan to investigate the risk and spread of the coronavirus, and their recommendations informed Wuhan's decision to "lock down" Wuhan on January 23.
The article concludes by emphasizing that in response to global health emergencies, countries need to strengthen global cooperation and joint response.
Reporter Yang Hong
