On the afternoon of the 25th local time, a small plane crashed into the top floor of a multi-storey residential building in Weisel County, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany, resulting in a total of three deaths.
Duisburg prosecutors, the Weisel County Police and the Weisel City Fire Department jointly issued a statement on the evening of the same day, saying that at around 14:40 that day, a two-seater small plane crashed into the residence on the top floor of a multi-storey residential building located in Huiberskamp Street in Weisel County, killing three people.
It took off from the city of Marr in the Ruhr district of North Rhine-Westphalia on the same day, stopped at the airport in the county of Wessel and took off again before crashing into a residential building.
The identity of the deceased may have been a female occupant of the house that had been impacted and two passengers on the small plane.
A two-year-old child in the room suffered only minor injuries and was rescued safely.
The rest of the occupants were not injured in the accident, but their emotions have not calmed down.
Footage from the scene, reported by the German news agency dpa, showed smoke billowing from the house where the accident occurred, and firefighters showed severe damage to the house after extinguishing the fire.
At the moment, the cause of the plane crash is not clear.
The Rheinische Post, citing police reports, said there were clues that the plane may have disintegrated before it crashed into a residential building.
Police said multiple parts of the crashed plane were found in the vicinity of the accident site.
The German criminal police are investigating the cause of the accident together with the Duisburg prosecutor and the German Federal Aviation Accident Investigation Agency.
