At the Zhuokang outpost in Balong, platoon commander Yu Wang and a soldier stood guard on duty.
In this place where the average annual temperature is more than 10 degrees below zero, a row of simple barracks stands in the mountain pass, and a national flag flutters in the wind not far from the barracks.
The warriors climbed the steep slope of the rubble, using both hands and feet.
It was late July, when flowers flourished at low altitudes, and in Barong Zhuokang, only in the ravine behind the barracks was relatively dense green.
Gao Peng, a soldier who had been stationed at the outpost for six years, pointed to the ravine and said that this was their back garden, and that the grass could only be seen slowly growing in July and August every year, and soon after, it would all turn yellow and be covered with snow.
Patrolling on foot can take about 9 hours.
In the harsh highland environment, the soldiers stationed here are accompanied by snow-capped mountains and glaciers all year round, and they regularly patrol the higher mountain passes.
A few days ago, a patrol team composed of 8 soldiers, under the leadership of instructor Liang Yixin, once again embarked on the patrol road.
Each soldier carried a weight of about 30 pounds and marched to the target point early in the morning.
On the way, a soldier was high-back, and his comrades were in emergency ambulance.
In addition to patrol duties, the soldiers at the Barong Zhuokang outpost undergo tactical and physical training on a daily basis.
As the minutes ticked by, the altitude continued to rise, the oxygen levels became lower and lower, and the physical strength was constantly overdrawn, these factors tested the will of the patrol members.
They gritted their teeth and persevered, and successively crossed several landslide points and several dangerous shoals.
At about 16 o'clock, it was lunch time for the patrol members, who took out their own dry food and sat on the spot at an altitude of more than 5,700 meters, accompanied by sleet, to replenish their strength with food.
Soldiers at the Chok Kang outpost in Barong undergo tactical and physical training.
During the break, they would play cards together, and the loser would do push-ups to entertain and exercise their fitness.
After a short rest in the cold wind, they climbed to the target point of the patrol, took out the national flag on the mountain pass, and solemnly swore an oath.
Behind them is the snow-capped mountains, and in front of them is a no-man's land of dozens of kilometers, and they are the safest guardians of the country.
